Yes @sureshsubbiah , with decimal supported, only CHAR is not supported for hive simple SQL type.
Then we will be free of CAST when reading from Hive. 
CHAR should be simple to add, I plan to do it next, or can be a good practice or beginners, 
And Trafodion now has native tinyint support, so that mapping can change also. We currently map Hive tinyint to Trafodion short.
All these type supporting are to simplify the bulkload as the most urgent purpose from my point of view. It is very time consuming to add multiple CAST to load data from Hive now.

Looks good to me. You could combine the TOK_INTERSECT and TOK_INTERSECT TOK_DISTINCT productions into one by adding a syntactic sugar production for the TOK_DISTINCT token. That would save you from repeating the semantic action for INTERSECT/INTERSECT DISTINCT.

For example:

| query_term TOK_INTERSECT distinct_sugar query_primary
{
   your nice semantic action here; with query_primary as $4
}

Then later

distinct_sugar: TOK_DISTINCT
                      | 
                      ;
(No semantic actions needed in this production.)

Looks good to me. But just wonder, if it is ok to the set these CQDs to 'ON" when it is set to 'OFF' in the master. I am assuming this takes care of scenario when these datatypes were created earlier when these CQDs was 'ON'

Hi @selvaganesang. If we don't set the CQDs to 'ON', and the master has them 'OFF', then we core. So, UPDATE STATISTICS is overriding anything set in the master unconditionally. UPDATE STATISTICS does this for several other CQDs as well. It wants to have tighter control over its environment. That said, someday I expect these particular CQDs to go away once all clients support the new data types.
